2227
01:48:45,600 --> 01:48:46,900
- Pardon me?
- Hold the phone.

2228
01:48:47,000 --> 01:48:48,600
- Okay, thank you.
- Okay.

2229
01:48:48,900 --> 01:48:51,500
I can give you a little time
tomorrow morning.

2230
01:48:51,600 --> 01:48:53,400
- I think that's Thursday.
- Yes.

2231
01:48:53,600 --> 01:48:56,000
- Let's say 8:30.
- Eight-thirty in the morning?

2232
01:48:56,100 --> 01:48:58,000
- Yeah. Okay?
- Okay. And just come here?

2233
01:48:58,000 --> 01:49:00,600
- Yes.
- Okay, good.

2234
01:49:04,100 --> 01:49:05,900
Hello?

2235
01:49:06,100 --> 01:49:08,500
Hi. It's Michael Moore here
to see Charlton Heston.

2236
01:49:08,600 --> 01:49:10,500
Okay.

2237
01:49:30,100 --> 01:49:32,500
Hi. Good morning.

2238
01:49:37,600 --> 01:49:39,900
- How are you?
- Fine.

2239
01:49:40,100 --> 01:49:42,300
Thank you very much
for agreeing to see me.

2240
01:49:50,500 --> 01:49:52,900
He took me out
to his pool-and-tennis house

2241
01:49:53,100 --> 01:49:54,900
so we could have a chat.

2242
01:49:55,000 --> 01:49:57,900
I told him that I was
a lifetime member of the NRA

2243
01:49:58,100 --> 01:50:00,200
and showed him
my membership card.

2244
01:50:00,400 --> 01:50:02,100
Good for you. Well done.

2245
01:50:02,300 --> 01:50:04,100
I assume you have guns
in the house here?

2246
01:50:04,400 --> 01:50:06,900
Indeed I do.
Bad guys take notice!

2247
01:50:07,000 --> 01:50:09,100
So you have them
for protection?

2248
01:50:09,300 --> 01:50:11,400
- Yeah. Sure.
- Have you ever been

2249
01:50:11,600 --> 01:50:13,500
- a victim of crime?
- No. No.

2250
01:50:13,600 --> 01:50:17,300
- Never been assaulted or...?
- No.

2251
01:50:17,600 --> 01:50:20,300
No violence toward you,
but you have guns in the house.

2252
01:50:20,500 --> 01:50:22,400
- Loaded.
- They're loaded?

2253
01:50:22,600 --> 01:50:24,900
Well, if you really needed
a weapon for self-defence,

2254
01:50:25,100 --> 01:50:26,900
- you need it loaded.
- Okay, but why...

2255
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:28,800
why do you need it for
self- defence? Because--

2256
01:50:29,000 --> 01:50:30,800
- I don't.
- Yeah, you've never been

2257
01:50:31,100 --> 01:50:32,900
a victim of crime,
you haven't been assaulted.

2258
01:50:33,100 --> 01:50:34,900
- No, that's true.
- You haven't been, you know...

2259
01:50:35,100 --> 01:50:38,400
Why would you... So why not...
Why don't you unload the gun?

2260
01:50:38,500 --> 01:50:41,800
Because the second amendment
gives me the right

2261
01:50:42,100 --> 01:50:43,900
- to have it loaded.
- I agree.

2262
01:50:44,100 --> 01:50:46,400
I totally agree with that.
I'm just saying... I mean,

2263
01:50:46,600 --> 01:50:47,900
the second amendment gives me--

2264
01:50:48,000 --> 01:50:49,800
Let's say it's
a comfort factor.

2265
01:50:50,100 --> 01:50:53,000
It gives you comfort to know
that there's a loaded gun.

2266
01:50:53,100 --> 01:50:54,400
Yeah.

2267
01:50:54,600 --> 01:50:57,500
Comfort meaning that it allows
you to relax and feel safe?

2268
01:50:57,600 --> 01:50:59,500
- Not worry about it.
- Not worry, not be afraid.

2269
01:50:59,600 --> 01:51:01,400
And I'm not really, but, uh...

2270
01:51:01,500 --> 01:51:05,900
I'm exercising one of the rights
passed on down to me

2271
01:51:06,100 --> 01:51:09,000
from those wise, old, dead white
guys that invented this country.

2272
01:51:09,100 --> 01:51:12,100
If it was good enough for them,
it's good enough for me.

2273
01:51:12,200 --> 01:51:13,800
But you could still
exercise the right,

2274
01:51:14,000 --> 01:51:16,400
just by having a gun unloaded
and locked away somewhere.

2275
01:51:16,600 --> 01:51:17,700
I choose to have it.

2276
01:51:17,900 --> 01:51:20,400
What sort of strikes me
as interesting is that,

2277
01:51:20,500 --> 01:51:23,400
in other countries, where
they don't have the murder rate,

2278
01:51:23,600 --> 01:51:25,400
the gun-murder rate
that we have, that, uh...

2279
01:51:25,600 --> 01:51:27,400
many people say,

2280
01:51:27,600 --> 01:51:29,400
"Well, that's because
they don't have guns around.

2281
01:51:29,600 --> 01:51:32,400
It's hard to get a gun in
Britain or Germany or whatever."

2282
01:51:32,600 --> 01:51:35,500
But we went to Canada and
there's seven million guns

2283
01:51:35,600 --> 01:51:38,500
- in 10-million homes.
- There won't be very long.

2284
01:51:38,600 --> 01:51:40,100
- But hear me out, though.
- Okay.

2285
01:51:40,400 --> 01:51:41,900
Canada is a nation of hunters,

2286
01:51:42,100 --> 01:51:43,900
millions of guns,

2287
01:51:44,100 --> 01:51:46,900
and yet, they had just
a few murders last year.

2288
01:51:47,100 --> 01:51:48,900
That's it. A country
of 30-million people.

2289
01:51:49,100 --> 01:51:51,800
Now, why - here's my question -
why is it that...

2290
01:51:52,100 --> 01:51:54,100
that they've got all these guns
laying around,

2291
01:51:54,200 --> 01:51:56,000
yet they don't kill each other

2292
01:51:56,200 --> 01:51:58,000
at the level that
we kill each other?

2293
01:51:58,100 --> 01:52:00,300
I think American history is...

2294
01:52:00,400 --> 01:52:02,800
uh... has a lot of blood

2295
01:52:03,000 --> 01:52:04,900
- on its hands.
- And Germany history doesn't?

2296
01:52:05,000 --> 01:52:06,800
- No.
- And British history?

2297
01:52:07,100 --> 01:52:09,400
- I don't think as much.
- Oh, are you...

2298
01:52:09,600 --> 01:52:12,000
Germans don't have as much,
blood on their hands?

2299
01:52:12,100 --> 01:52:14,500
- Uh, they do, yes.
- The Brits, they ruled the world

2300
01:52:14,600 --> 01:52:16,800
for 300 years
at the barrel of a gun.

2301
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:20,300
They're all violent people. They
have bad guys, they have crime,

2302
01:52:20,500 --> 01:52:22,800
they have lots of guns--

2303
01:52:23,000 --> 01:52:26,800
Well, it's an interesting
point, which can be explored

2304
01:52:27,000 --> 01:52:30,300
and you're good to explore it
at great lengths,

2305
01:52:30,500 --> 01:52:33,300
but I think that's about all
I have to say on it.

2306
01:52:33,500 --> 01:52:36,300
You don't have any opinion,
though, as to why that is,

2307
01:52:36,500 --> 01:52:38,300
that we are the unique country,
the only country,

2308
01:52:38,500 --> 01:52:41,300
that does this, that kills each
other on this level, with guns?

2309
01:52:41,500 --> 01:52:45,300
Well, we have, probably,
more mixed ethnicity

2310
01:52:45,500 --> 01:52:48,800
than other countries,
some other countries.

2311
01:52:49,100 --> 01:52:50,900
You think it's an ethnic thing?

2312
01:52:50,900 --> 01:52:52,700
No, I don't. It's...

2313
01:52:53,000 --> 01:52:54,800
I wouldn't go so far
as to say that.

2314
01:52:55,100 --> 01:52:58,300
We had enough problems with
civil rights in the beginning.

2315
01:52:58,600 --> 01:53:02,300
It's... But, uh, I have
no answer for that.

2316
01:53:02,600 --> 01:53:04,800
What do you mean, you think
it's a mixed ethnicity?

2317
01:53:05,000 --> 01:53:06,900
I don't understand.

2318
01:53:07,000 --> 01:53:08,900
- You said, "How is it that..."
- That we're unique.

2319
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:12,100
"So many Americans
kill each other?"

2320
01:53:12,200 --> 01:53:15,200
I don't know that that's true,
but, uh...

2321
01:53:15,400 --> 01:53:16,800
Well, no, you know that.

2322
01:53:16,900 --> 01:53:19,800
We know we have the highest
murder rate with guns.

2323
01:53:19,900 --> 01:53:21,700
It's way higher
than any other country.

2324
01:53:21,900 --> 01:53:25,300
The only answer I can give you
is the one I already gave you.

2325
01:53:25,600 --> 01:53:28,400
- Which is?
- Which is that we have, uh...

2326
01:53:28,500 --> 01:53:31,300
- Historically--
- ...a history of violence.

2327
01:53:31,400 --> 01:53:34,500
Perhaps more than most
countries. Not more than Russia,

2328
01:53:34,800 --> 01:53:37,800
- not more than Japan or China--
- Not more than Germany.

2329
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:42,400
Not more than Germany,
but certainly more than Canada.

2330
01:53:42,700 --> 01:53:45,300
I come from Flint, Michigan,
and last year,

2331
01:53:45,500 --> 01:53:48,400
a little six-year-old boy
took a gun into a classroom

2332
01:53:48,500 --> 01:53:51,300
and shot and killed a
six-year-old girl. And, uh...

2333
01:53:51,600 --> 01:53:53,800
it was really a tragic thing--

2334
01:53:53,900 --> 01:53:56,900
- This was a kid, though.
- A six-year-old, yeah.

2335
01:53:57,000 --> 01:53:58,400
Did you hear about this?

2336
01:53:58,600 --> 01:54:01,200
A six-year-old shooting
a six-year-old?

2337
01:54:01,400 --> 01:54:02,800
- Yeah.
- Well, here's my question.

2338
01:54:02,900 --> 01:54:03,800
After that happened,

2339
01:54:04,000 --> 01:54:05,800
you came to Flint
and held a big rally.

2340
01:54:06,000 --> 01:54:07,300
Mm-hm.

2341
01:54:07,500 --> 01:54:09,800
And, you know, I just--

2342
01:54:10,000 --> 01:54:12,400
So did the vice-president.

2343
01:54:12,500 --> 01:54:15,100
Yeah, but did you feel it was
being at all insensitive

2344
01:54:15,200 --> 01:54:17,900
to the fact that this community
had just gone through--

2345
01:54:18,100 --> 01:54:20,800
Actually, I wasn't aware
of that at the time we came.

2346
01:54:20,900 --> 01:54:24,300
We came and did an
early-morning, uh... rally,

2347
01:54:24,400 --> 01:54:26,200
then went on to wherever
we were going.

2348
01:54:26,400 --> 01:54:29,300
You didn't know at the time,
that this killing had happened?

2349
01:54:29,400 --> 01:54:31,300
- No.
- Had you known, would you have--

2350
01:54:31,400 --> 01:54:33,300
Would I have cancelled
the... uh...

2351
01:54:33,400 --> 01:54:35,200
- Yeah.
- I don't...

2352
01:54:35,400 --> 01:54:36,700
Hard to say.

2353
01:54:36,800 --> 01:54:38,700
It wasn't like it was
already planned.

2354
01:54:38,900 --> 01:54:40,800
I mean, the choice to come there
was made

2355
01:54:40,900 --> 01:54:42,700
after this horrible
killing took place.

2356
01:54:43,000 --> 01:54:44,300
Yeah. Mm-hm.

2357
01:54:44,500 --> 01:54:47,300
You know, had you know that,
would you have come?

2358
01:54:47,400 --> 01:54:50,200
I don't know. I have no idea.

2359
01:54:50,500 --> 01:54:52,300
- Maybe not. Maybe not.
- Okay. Thank you.

2360
01:54:52,600 --> 01:54:55,800
You think you'd like to just
maybe apologize to the people

2361
01:54:55,900 --> 01:54:58,700
in Flint for coming and doing
that at that time, or...?

2362
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:00,700
You want me to apologize...

2363
01:55:00,900 --> 01:55:02,700
me, apologize to the people
in Flint?

2364
01:55:03,000 --> 01:55:04,800
Or the people in Columbine

2365
01:55:05,000 --> 01:55:07,300
for coming after
their horrible tragedy.

2366
01:55:07,400 --> 01:55:09,800
Why do you go to the places
after they have

2367
01:55:09,900 --> 01:55:12,300
these horrible tragedies? I'm
a member of your group here--

2368
01:55:12,400 --> 01:55:15,000
Well, I'm afraid
we don't agree on... on that.

2369
01:55:15,100 --> 01:55:17,700
You think it's okay
to just come and show up

2370
01:55:17,900 --> 01:55:20,300
- at these events.
- No.

2371
01:55:20,400 --> 01:55:22,300
You don't think it's okay?

2372
01:55:33,200 --> 01:55:35,900
Mr. Heston, just one more thing.

2373
01:55:36,100 --> 01:55:37,900
This is who she is -

2374
01:55:38,100 --> 01:55:40,700
or was. This is her.

2375
01:55:40,800 --> 01:55:42,700
Mr. Heston, please don't leave.

2376
01:55:42,900 --> 01:55:45,500
Mr. Heston, please,
take a look at her.

2377
01:55:45,700 --> 01:55:48,200
This is the girl.

2378
01:56:39,300 --> 01:56:42,700
I left the Heston estate
atop Beverly Hills

2379
01:56:42,900 --> 01:56:44,800
and walked back
into the real world,

2380
01:56:44,900 --> 01:56:48,200
an America living
and breathing in fear...

2381
01:56:48,300 --> 01:56:50,200
In your mind,
you imagine somebody

2382
01:56:50,300 --> 01:56:53,200
who might break into your house,
to harm you or your family.

2383
01:56:53,300 --> 01:56:56,700
What does that person look like?

2384
01:56:56,900 --> 01:56:59,500
You. Her. Him.
The camera guy, anybody.

2385
01:56:59,600 --> 01:57:02,200
Could be a gun in the camera,
